{{}}   This document goes on to list antebellum plantation architecture in Natchez, Mississippi; small rural French towns in Teche Parish, Louisiana; industrial themes in Birmingham, Alabama; and a cotton plantation in South Carolina, as objectives of the proposed trip for gathering still photography of a &ldquo;general sociological nature.&rdquo; In early 1936, one of Middletown's authors had a chance to directly affect the RA's Photography Section: Stryker showed Robert Lynd, a former Columbia colleague, some RA pictures and asked for his opinion while lunching with him in New York. The result was a &ldquo;shooting script&rdquo; for &ldquo;things which should be photographed as American Background,&rdquo; issued by Stryker to his team of photographers. The script contains an extensive listing of items like &ldquo;People on and off the job,&rdquo; &ldquo;How do people look?,&rdquo; &ldquo;The wall decoration in homes as an index to the different income groups and their reactions,&rdquo; and &ldquo;A photographic study of use of leisure time in various income groups.&quot;5
